00:33:13.819 --> 00:33:14.643
<v ->Yes.</v>

777
00:33:14.643 --> 00:33:16.849
<v Voiceover>So if you could just tell Andy's story.</v>

778
00:33:16.849 --> 00:33:17.789
<v ->The Andy story.</v>

779
00:33:17.789 --> 00:33:22.789
Well, Andy was in a group of Vietnam veterans

780
00:33:23.223 --> 00:33:25.858
who were what we call dual diagnosis.

781
00:33:25.858 --> 00:33:30.154
They were all in recovery for massive substance abuse

782
00:33:30.154 --> 00:33:33.196
and had been through a program that dried them out

783
00:33:33.196 --> 00:33:36.435
and then if they qualified they entered this

784
00:33:36.435 --> 00:33:38.768
called Transcend Vietnam program.

785
00:33:38.768 --> 00:33:41.613
This was at the Louis B. Stokes VA Hospital

786
00:33:41.613 --> 00:33:43.447
in Brecksville, Ohio.

787
00:33:43.447 --> 00:33:47.778
So Andy was one of these guys,

788
00:33:47.778 --> 00:33:50.982
very, very much a leader.

789
00:33:50.982 --> 00:33:52.724
He was so tuned into himself

790
00:33:52.724 --> 00:33:55.487
and he was so authentic

791
00:33:55.487 --> 00:33:57.217
that he was a natural leader.

792
00:33:57.217 --> 00:33:58.598
And as I said this morning,

793
00:33:58.598 --> 00:34:00.827
he's the kind of person you would pay

794
00:34:00.827 --> 00:34:02.569
to have in your therapy group

795
00:34:02.569 --> 00:34:05.971
'cause he catalyzes all kinds of movement

796
00:34:05.971 --> 00:34:09.105
and speaks for everybody and tells the truth

797
00:34:09.105 --> 00:34:11.334
and you could tell, even though I think at the time

798
00:34:11.334 --> 00:34:15.580
he was in his 40's, now he's in his 50's,

799
00:34:15.580 --> 00:34:17.415
but oh maybe he's in his 60's.

800
00:34:17.415 --> 00:34:19.841
Anyway, whatever he was,

801
00:34:19.841 --> 00:34:21.246
he 'was like an 18-year-old kid still.

802
00:34:21.246 --> 00:34:24.148
You could see where he got his development was arrested

803
00:34:24.148 --> 00:34:28.653
and he still had this sort of sweet, unformed

804
00:34:28.653 --> 00:34:32.554
18-year-old blue collar kid flavor to him

805
00:34:32.554 --> 00:34:34.493
that was very appealing.

806
00:34:34.493 --> 00:34:38.429
Anyway, so Andy's in this group

807
00:34:38.429 --> 00:34:39.996
and at some point in the group,

808
00:34:39.996 --> 00:34:42.597
the group all becomes very skilled at guided imagery,

809
00:34:42.597 --> 00:34:45.673
they do a lot of other things, they do journaling,

810
00:34:45.673 --> 00:34:46.846
but one of the things they do

811
00:34:46.846 --> 00:34:48.680
is towards the end of the group,

812
00:34:48.680 --> 00:34:50.550
and it was an eight-week group,

813
00:34:50.550 --> 00:34:54.311
they talk about their trauma or some core traumas

814
00:34:54.311 --> 00:34:57.388
and Andy never knew until the last minute

815
00:34:57.388 --> 00:34:58.955
whether he was even gonna talk about this

816
00:34:58.955 --> 00:35:00.650
because he had never talked about it,

817
00:35:00.650 --> 00:35:02.519
it was so horrible.

818
00:35:02.519 --> 00:35:05.793
But at the very tail end of the final session

819
00:35:05.793 --> 00:35:08.232
he tells his story, which is

820
00:35:08.232 --> 00:35:11.436
he's walking point, which is what you do

821
00:35:11.436 --> 00:35:14.536
when you send somebody out ahead of everybody else

822
00:35:14.536 --> 00:35:18.274
to make sure that things are safe for the group to proceed.

823
00:35:18.274 --> 00:35:21.641
He was one of these guys who became

824
00:35:21.641 --> 00:35:25.008
sort of wildly, mystically attuned to the environment.

825
00:35:25.008 --> 00:35:27.411
He could smell danger.

826
00:35:27.411 --> 00:35:31.417
He was so, and he would become elated at this job.

827
00:35:31.417 --> 00:35:32.752
Nobody else wanted to walk point,

828
00:35:32.752 --> 00:35:34.284
but he always volunteered.

829
00:35:34.284 --> 00:35:39.284
And he had this very attuned

830
00:35:39.962 --> 00:35:43.561
and exquisite sensibility walking point

831
00:35:43.561 --> 00:35:45.395
and I think that's because he had so much adrenaline

832
00:35:45.395 --> 00:35:48.599
going through him that he was in this psychic,

833
00:35:48.599 --> 00:35:51.200
intuitive state of mind.

834
00:35:51.200 --> 00:35:52.837
Anyway, and people thought he was crazy

835
00:35:52.837 --> 00:35:54.904
'cause he would walk point not with a machine gun,

836
00:35:54.904 --> 00:35:57.481
but with a single rocket launcher because

837
00:35:57.481 --> 00:36:00.685
(laughs) okay.

838
00:36:00.685 --> 00:36:05.685
But basically everybody thought Andy was nuts,

839
00:36:05.782 --> 00:36:07.918
but they always liked it better when he walked point

840
00:36:07.918 --> 00:36:10.786
'cause they knew that they were safe with him,

841
00:36:10.786 --> 00:36:13.097
in his little 18-year-old hands.

842
00:36:13.097 --> 00:36:18.097
Anyway, so he had this unique role in his group

843
00:36:19.830 --> 00:36:23.104
and at one point, this was the trauma,

844
00:36:23.104 --> 00:36:26.042
they come across a 10-year-old girl

845
00:36:26.042 --> 00:36:31.042
who was not supposed to know any Americans were there.

846
00:36:31.475 --> 00:36:36.475
They knew that if she was allowed to live

847
00:36:36.537 --> 00:36:39.114
that she would reveal their location,

848
00:36:39.114 --> 00:36:41.460
hundreds of troops would be killed.

849
00:36:41.460 --> 00:36:44.525
So they were being, basically this group of men

850
00:36:44.525 --> 00:36:46.255
were being given a choice

851
00:36:46.255 --> 00:36:49.529
that no one should ever have to make

852
00:36:49.529 --> 00:36:53.197
and they tied her up to a tree.

853
00:36:53.197 --> 00:36:54.997
They tried, nobody knew what to do,

854
00:36:54.997 --> 00:36:57.156
so they just shuffled around.

855
00:36:57.156 --> 00:36:58.875
Nobody wanted to hurt her.

856
00:36:58.875 --> 00:37:02.567
And as usual, Andy, in his leadership way,

857
00:37:02.567 --> 00:37:04.482
stepped, came forward,

858
00:37:04.482 --> 00:37:06.050
everybody else backed off,

859
00:37:06.050 --> 00:37:08.383
got as far away from there as they could,

860
00:37:08.383 --> 00:37:10.682
and he just squatted

861
00:37:10.682 --> 00:37:12.551
about a foot and a half away from this girl

862
00:37:12.551 --> 00:37:15.686
and just stared her in the eye

863
00:37:15.686 --> 00:37:19.889
and was trying to sort of commune with her

864
00:37:19.889 --> 00:37:21.514
and see what her intentions were,

865
00:37:21.514 --> 00:37:26.332
if there was anything they could do to let her go.

866
00:37:26.332 --> 00:37:31.034
And they had this intense eyeball to eyeball contact

867
00:37:31.034 --> 00:37:33.739
and basically what he saw was

868
00:37:33.739 --> 00:37:38.546
this steely, flinty little warrior girl

869
00:37:38.546 --> 00:37:41.112
who was basically looking him in the eye

870
00:37:41.112 --> 00:37:45.477
and saying with her eyes, "Go to hell."

871
00:37:45.477 --> 00:37:49.726
So he knew that this was the problem

872
00:37:49.726 --> 00:37:51.387
and at some point, he doesn't,

873
00:37:51.387 --> 00:37:54.219
and he also felt that this was a perfect mirror.

874
00:37:54.219 --> 00:37:56.425
This was, he was looking at himself,

875
00:37:56.425 --> 00:37:59.885
this incredibly intelligent

876
00:37:59.885 --> 00:38:04.204
and vitally courageous little girl.

877
00:38:04.204 --> 00:38:09.173
So at some point, and he isn't sure what it was,

878
00:38:09.173 --> 00:38:11.646
it might have been 10 minutes, it might have been an hour,

879
00:38:11.646 --> 00:38:13.678
he slit her throat with his knife

880
00:38:13.678 --> 00:38:16.151
and walked back to the other men

881
00:38:16.151 --> 00:38:18.821
with her blood on his hands

882
00:38:18.821 --> 00:38:20.551
and they wouldn't look at him.

883
00:38:20.551 --> 00:38:21.921
Nobody spoke about it.

884
00:38:21.921 --> 00:38:25.195
They never spoke about it and they just kept going.

885
00:38:25.195 --> 00:38:28.701
And Andy's traumatic, intrusive memory

886
00:38:28.701 --> 00:38:31.197
and his nightmares and his flashbacks

887
00:38:31.197 --> 00:38:33.972
were of this little girl's eyes,

888
00:38:33.972 --> 00:38:38.070
staring at him, following him, accusing him,

889
00:38:38.070 --> 00:38:41.944
and never giving him a moment's peace,

890
00:38:41.944 --> 00:38:44.278
asleep or awake.

891
00:38:44.278 --> 00:38:46.716
So Andy basically did some imagery,

892
00:38:46.716 --> 00:38:48.945
one-on-one imagery in the room

893
00:38:48.945 --> 00:38:53.926
where he met with this girl again

894
00:38:53.926 --> 00:38:57.757
and he asked her forgiveness,

895
00:38:57.757 --> 00:39:02.757
told her his great sorrow about having done his regret,

896
00:39:03.222 --> 00:39:06.252
about having done what he did to her,

897
00:39:06.252 --> 00:39:08.400
telling her how much he admired her courage

898
00:39:08.400 --> 00:39:11.610
and her strength and her steeliness

899
00:39:11.610 --> 00:39:14.640
and how much he connected to that

900
00:39:14.640 --> 00:39:18.169
and basically told her he was sorry,

901
00:39:18.169 --> 00:39:19.981
he was so sorry.

902
00:39:19.981 --> 00:39:24.981
And the shift came when right after doing that imagery.

903
00:39:25.182 --> 00:39:26.680
What he reported was

904
00:39:26.680 --> 00:39:29.559
the girl's eyes were still following him,

905
00:39:29.559 --> 00:39:31.927
but they were eyes of forgiveness,

906
00:39:31.927 --> 00:39:33.657
they were very sorrowful,

907
00:39:33.657 --> 00:39:35.724
and they were basically eyes that said,

908
00:39:35.724 --> 00:39:37.187
"I know what you've been through

909
00:39:37.187 --> 00:39:40.658
"and you shouldn't have had to have been through this."

910
00:39:40.658 --> 00:39:42.005
And so they were not just,

911
00:39:42.005 --> 00:39:44.838
they weren't these eyes that accused him.

912
00:39:44.838 --> 00:39:47.636
He now had eyes that were his companions

913
00:39:47.636 --> 00:39:50.097
and provided him with huge solace.

914
00:39:50.097 --> 00:39:52.581
And I have to tell you, this was a long time ago

915
00:39:52.581 --> 00:39:54.311
that I heard this story.

916
00:39:54.311 --> 00:39:59.311
This was like in close to I think it was 1999.

917
00:40:00.012 --> 00:40:04.795
But I just got a picture of Andy,

918
00:40:04.795 --> 00:40:06.490
that's not his real name,

919
00:40:06.490 --> 00:40:09.555
I just got a picture of Andy and his new girlfriend

920
00:40:09.555 --> 00:40:11.831
in his location, in his new city,

921
00:40:11.831 --> 00:40:13.572
and he just looked like a different person.

922
00:40:13.572 --> 00:40:15.465
He didn't look like an 18-year-old kid anymore.

923
00:40:15.465 --> 00:40:16.925
He looked like a guy.

924
00:40:16.925 --> 00:40:19.293
He looked like a guy almost his own age

925
00:40:19.293 --> 00:40:21.174
and very happy

926
00:40:21.174 --> 00:40:22.671
and a very sweet note.

927
00:40:22.671 --> 00:40:24.041
<v Voiceover>Aw, very sweet note.</v>

928
00:40:24.041 --> 00:40:26.445
Now that's something that, as you say,

929
00:40:26.445 --> 00:40:27.942
no one should have to live through.

930
00:40:27.942 --> 00:40:28.616
<v ->No.</v>

931
00:40:28.616 --> 00:40:33.585
<v Voiceover>And yet, even he was able to turn this into</v>

932
00:40:33.585 --> 00:40:36.044
an experience that ended up being his friend.

933
00:40:36.044 --> 00:40:39.596
<v ->Yes, and it allowed him to forgive himself.</v>

934
00:40:39.596 --> 00:40:43.068
And let me tell you, this is not that unusual an experience.

935
00:40:43.068 --> 00:40:46.969
Our guys are coming home from Afghanistan and Iraq

936
00:40:46.969 --> 00:40:49.035
having had to make these choices

937
00:40:49.035 --> 00:40:52.135
or having been completely in some kind of war fog,

938
00:40:52.135 --> 00:40:55.212
out of control, doing things they never would have done--

939
00:40:55.212 --> 00:40:56.315
<v Voiceover>And they take it home.</v>

940
00:40:56.315 --> 00:40:58.044
And you're talking violence at home,

941
00:40:58.044 --> 00:40:59.879
you're talking a lot of problems.

942
00:40:59.879 --> 00:41:01.446
<v ->Yeah, and suicide at home,</v>

943
00:41:01.446 --> 00:41:03.014
and self hatred at home,

944
00:41:03.014 --> 00:41:06.020
and absolute disconnect from self at home.

945
00:41:06.020 --> 00:41:09.852
And these things need to be addressed

946
00:41:09.852 --> 00:41:11.454
in a way that helps.

947
00:41:11.454 --> 00:41:12.661
Talking about it won't help.

948
00:41:12.661 --> 00:41:14.798
Most of these people can't talk about it.

949
00:41:14.798 --> 00:41:16.957
Yesterday at a workshop, someone came up to me

950
00:41:16.957 --> 00:41:21.032
and said that her son, who came back from Iraq,

951
00:41:21.032 --> 00:41:22.634
got the guided imagery

952
00:41:22.634 --> 00:41:26.175
and he's listened to it 700 times.

953
00:41:26.175 --> 00:41:27.708
That's all he wants to do.

954
00:41:27.708 --> 00:41:28.637
Now, some people do that.

955
00:41:28.637 --> 00:41:30.297
They just listen to it over and over again

956
00:41:30.297 --> 00:41:33.246
until it thunks in and makes the shift.

957
00:41:33.246 --> 00:41:34.686
<v Voiceover>It's probably the only relief.</v>

958
00:41:34.686 --> 00:41:35.614
<v ->Yeah.</v>

959
00:41:35.614 --> 00:41:37.553
But other people, and other people find it

960
00:41:37.553 --> 00:41:39.550
a little bit too intense right away.

961
00:41:39.550 --> 00:41:41.454
They have to titrate the dosage.

962
00:41:41.454 --> 00:41:43.823
They listen to it a little bit more each day.

963
00:41:43.823 --> 00:41:46.493
And other people,

964
00:41:46.493 --> 00:41:48.025
other people don't need it.

965
00:41:48.025 --> 00:41:50.266
Other people come home and there's something

966
00:41:50.266 --> 00:41:53.227
in their nervous system and their biochemistr

967
00:41:53.227 --> 00:41:54.701
that settles out.

968
00:41:54.701 --> 00:41:56.907
A lot of this is physiologic.

969
00:41:56.907 --> 00:42:00.274
<v Voiceover>I've read about this, the phenomena,</v>

970
00:42:00.274 --> 00:42:03.211
I read about it recently in the paper,

971
00:42:03.211 --> 00:42:05.243
that the people who choose combat,

972
00:42:05.243 --> 00:42:07.519
for example, the really intense forms,

973
00:42:07.519 --> 00:42:09.713
the SEALs, Green Berets and so forth,

974
00:42:09.713 --> 00:42:13.521
don't experience this kind of stress in their beings.

975
00:42:13.521 --> 00:42:15.994
They're prepared for it, they're wired for it,

976
00:42:15.994 --> 00:42:17.027
they're ready for it.

977
00:42:17.027 --> 00:42:18.455
Those who are drafted,

978
00:42:18.455 --> 00:42:19.953
those who end up there when they thought

979
00:42:19.953 --> 00:42:24.234
they were gonna just be in Fort Dix or whatever,

980
00:42:24.234 --> 00:42:25.429
whole different deal.

981
00:42:25.429 --> 00:42:26.231
<v ->Right, that's true.</v>

982
00:42:26.231 --> 00:42:27.635
<v Voiceover>Didn't really up for this</v>

983
00:42:27.635 --> 00:42:29.365
and they're not prepared.

984
00:42:29.365 --> 00:42:31.533
<v ->For the most part, but not,</v>

985
00:42:31.533 --> 00:42:34.644
there are so many anomalies that even to say

986
00:42:34.644 --> 00:42:38.174
there are Marines, there are SEALS who get PTSD,

987
00:42:38.174 --> 00:42:41.448
but it does, generally speaking, take more.

988
00:42:41.448 --> 00:42:44.426
Women are twice as likely to get PTSD as men.

989
00:42:44.426 --> 00:42:48.211
Children are twice as likely to get PTSD as adults.

990
00:42:48.211 --> 00:42:50.718
Some of it has to do with just the neurophysiology,

991
00:42:50.718 --> 00:42:51.995
the way the brain is wired,

992
00:42:51.995 --> 00:42:55.664
and the way the biolchemicals get mixed.

993
00:42:55.664 --> 00:42:57.696
So a lot of it's in the hardwiring

994
00:42:57.696 --> 00:43:01.330
and people tend to blame themselves for getting PTSD.

995
00:43:01.330 --> 00:43:02.499
They say, "Oh I should have known,"

996
00:43:02.499 --> 00:43:04.798
or for whatever happened they should have known better,

997
00:43:04.798 --> 00:43:08.362
"I should have been smarter, I should have been wiser."

998
00:43:08.362 --> 00:43:10.475
It's not a choice.

999
00:43:10.475 --> 00:43:12.078
<v Voiceover>And this is something that encompasses</v>

1000
00:43:12.078 --> 00:43:15.711
all of the truly shocking events of our lives,

1001
00:43:15.711 --> 00:43:17.186
whether it is a car accident

1002
00:43:17.186 --> 00:43:18.858
or whether it's even emotional trauma

1003
00:43:18.858 --> 00:43:20.123
that's been introduced.

1004
00:43:20.123 --> 00:43:22.259
<v ->Yeah, it has to be something,</v>

1005
00:43:22.259 --> 00:43:24.825
I mean to qualify as a catalyst for PTSD,

1006
00:43:24.825 --> 00:43:27.995
it has to be something that turns your life upside down

1007
00:43:27.995 --> 00:43:31.536
and leaves you absolutely without the platform

1008
00:43:31.536 --> 00:43:33.402
you normally stood on,

1009
00:43:33.402 --> 00:43:35.399
you know, without your self identity.

1010
00:43:35.399 --> 00:43:38.302
It just shifts something huge about yourself

1011
00:43:38.302 --> 00:43:41.169
and that could be 9/11, it could be Hurricane Katrina.

1012
00:43:41.169 --> 00:43:43.445
<v Voiceover>Weren't your CDs handed out</v>

1013
00:43:43.445 --> 00:43:44.339
by the Red Cross?
<v ->Yes.</v>

1014
00:43:44.339 --> 00:43:45.512
<v Voiceover>Is that correct?</v>
<v ->Yes.</v>

1015
00:43:45.512 --> 00:43:48.414
By the Red Cross and by John Jay College of Criminal Justice

1016
00:43:48.414 --> 00:43:51.851
to early responders and survivors at 9/11

1017
00:43:51.851 --> 00:43:53.453
and for the people working on the pile

1018
00:43:53.453 --> 00:43:55.647
for like years afterwards.

1019
00:43:55.647 --> 00:43:59.026
And they're still being handed out.

1020
00:43:59.026 --> 00:44:02.196
There's a lot of the post-traumatic stress from 9/11

1021
00:44:02.196 --> 00:44:05.400
is just emerging now because it does go underground

1022
00:44:05.400 --> 00:44:07.153
in many instances

1023
00:44:07.153 --> 00:44:09.672
and so people who think they're doing okay

1024
00:44:09.672 --> 00:44:12.703
all of the sudden one day, maybe five years later,

1025
00:44:12.703 --> 00:44:13.875
boom.

1026
00:44:13.875 --> 00:44:18.875
So there's a lot of people just reporting PTSD now.

1027
00:44:19.645 --> 00:44:22.850
<v Voiceover>Would you say that on some level,</v>

1028
00:44:22.850 --> 00:44:24.046
to much lesser degrees

1029
00:44:24.046 --> 00:44:26.391
and not to qualify for that particular label,

1030
00:44:26.391 --> 00:44:29.224
but most all of us have some kind of trauma

1031
00:44:29.224 --> 00:44:32.927
and wounds in our lives that are unresolved.

1032
00:44:32.927 --> 00:44:35.667
<v ->We all certainly have huge losses</v>

1033
00:44:35.667 --> 00:44:38.930
and greatly stressful experiences,

1034
00:44:38.930 --> 00:44:43.632
but post-traumatic stress is a very unique configuration

1035
00:44:43.632 --> 00:44:45.304
of hideous stuff

1036
00:44:45.304 --> 00:44:49.007
and for reasons that sometimes seem arbitrary.

1037
00:44:49.007 --> 00:44:51.631
It gets distinguished from acute stress.

1038
00:44:51.631 --> 00:44:54.650
So for instance, after a hurricane

1039
00:44:54.650 --> 00:44:57.715
or a cyclone that are very destructive,

1040
00:44:57.715 --> 00:44:59.851
almost everybody is going to have acute stress

1041
00:44:59.851 --> 00:45:02.893
and insane hormone levels

1042
00:45:02.893 --> 00:45:06.062
from four to eight months afterwards,

1043
00:45:06.062 --> 00:45:09.835
but for most people it settles down in and of itself.

1044
00:45:09.835 --> 00:45:12.297
People who go on to get PTSD,

1045
00:45:12.297 --> 00:45:15.966
it just never, the cycling never stops

1046
00:45:15.966 --> 00:45:17.266
and there's something about

1047
00:45:17.266 --> 00:45:20.493
sort of an irritated neuronal network

1048
00:45:20.493 --> 00:45:22.641
or maybe some inherited hardwiring

1049
00:45:22.641 --> 00:45:26.345
that just makes some people more vulnerable

1050
00:45:26.345 --> 00:45:27.645
and there are some things that make people

1051
00:45:27.645 --> 00:45:29.886
less vulnerable.

1052
00:45:29.886 --> 00:45:31.349
<v Voiceover>So, I'm sorry go ahead.</v>

1053
00:45:31.349 --> 00:45:34.507
<v ->I was telling you there's a big study of nightclub fires</v>

1054
00:45:34.507 --> 00:45:38.895
that show that people who are inebriated do not get PTSD

1055
00:45:38.895 --> 00:45:42.227
even if they had a horrific experience

1056
00:45:42.227 --> 00:45:44.189
and just got out with their lives

1057
00:45:44.189 --> 00:45:48.740
and are burned horribly, they still don't get PTSD

1058
00:45:48.740 --> 00:45:49.867
if they were drunk.

1059
00:45:49.867 --> 00:45:51.202
<v Voiceover>That makes sense, that makes sense</v>

1060
00:45:51.202 --> 00:45:53.245
because it wasn't striking them emotionally

1061
00:45:53.245 --> 00:45:55.811
in that shocking manner as if you were--

1062
00:45:55.811 --> 00:45:59.282
<v ->Or I would take it even a step more primitively</v>

1063
00:45:59.282 --> 00:46:03.148
and say there was some substance

1064
00:46:03.148 --> 00:46:05.923
in their bloodstream that interfered

1065
00:46:05.923 --> 00:46:09.824
with this flooding of biochemicals that normally occurs

1066
00:46:09.824 --> 00:46:11.554
that gets this whole thing rolling.

1067
00:46:11.554 --> 00:46:12.831
<v Voiceover>Absolutely.</v>

1068
00:46:12.831 --> 00:46:16.001
Well, where are you headed right now

1069
00:46:16.001 --> 00:46:17.789
